				for World War I.</abstract>
		</did>
		<bioghist encodinganalog="545">
			<head>Administrative History</head>
			<p>The Vassar College Training Camp for Nurses was the result of a Vassar Alumnae
				Association request to have the college campus used to aid the war effort during the
				summer of 1918. A committee was formed to investigate various options, and in the
				end the nursing program was chosen because it targeted college women and would
				provide them with skills of continued use after the war. The program was endorsed by
				the Council of National Defense (CND), the Red Cross, as well as several hospitals.
				The CND appointed a committee of medical educators to formulate the curriculum.
				Members included Isabel M. Stewart (Columbia University), Elizabeth Burgess (New
				York State Inspector of Training Schools), and Annie Strong (Simmons College).
				Recruiting, fund-raising and publicity responsibilities were handed to a group of
				alumnae which included Ada Thurston, Mabel Kirk, and Minnie Blodgett. Vassar
				undergraduates contributed as well by volunteering at the farm and dairy in order to
				feed the participants. The program itself was an intensive 3-month series of courses
				followed by another year of practical training at the affiliated hospitals.</p>
		</bioghist>
		<scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
			<head>Scope and Content Note</head>
			<p>Correspondence, news clippings, reports, printed material and photographs relating to
				Vassar College's Training Camp for Nurses.</p>
		</scopecontent>
